title: For Sale/Trade:  1974 Marlin Model 99M1 w/ Original Rear Sight
location: Jaffrey-Rindge Area, New Hampshire, United States
postcontent: This is a very nice example of a Marlin Model 99M1 semi-automatic 22LR rifle, complete with the original rear sight. Rear sights for this model are rare, because they were usually removed, in order to add a rimfire scope, and subsequently lost. To find an original rear sight by itself can cost almost as much as the rifle.   Based on the serial number (26431xxx) and Marlin's use of coding for dating production, this particular Model 99M1 was produced in 1974. It is my understanding that, after 1972, Marlin used the first two digits of the serial number subtracted from 100 to indicate the year of manufacture.   The tube magazine has a 9 rounds capacity with an 18" barrel. All of the metal parts, including the barrel, receiver, trigger guard and sling loops were professionally stripped and parkerized by the previous owner. While not original to the 99M1, I believe it makes it look more "GI" in appearance and suits the rifle.   There are some minor chips around the muzzle, but overall condition of the finish is 98%. The walnut stock has the original finish with some minor handling marks, but no cracks, gouges or major defects. The butt plate is original and has no cracks or chips. Includes a surplus OD green strap. I have tried to provide quality photos, so that you can examine it for yourself.   Must have NH License, face-to-face transaction. Prefer local to the Monadnock Region.   If this listing is still active, the item is still available.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Kel Tec PF9 w/Don Hume holster
postcontent:
I've own this gun for a few years now and it has been very reliable.
It's only got about 200 rounds through it and has been very well maintained.
It comes with the case, 2 magazines, single mag holder and a left handed Don Hume IWB holster.
If you don't want the holster deduct $40 off price.
Must have WI ID or driver's license and CCW card.


The PF-9 is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the 9mm Luger cartridge. It has been developed from our highly successful P-11 and P-3AT pistols with maximum concealability in mind. The PF-9 has a single stack magazine holding 7 rounds. It is one of the lightest and flattest 9 mm ever made. Firing mechanism is Double-Action Only with an automatic hammer block safety. The PF-9 is available in blued, parkerized, and hard chrome finishes. Grips are in black, grey, and olive drab.


The PF-9 retains the best features from our P-11 and P-3AT pistols combined into the flattest and lightest single stack 9mm configuration ever made. The barrel, locking system, slide stop, assembly pin, front sight, recoil springs and guide rod are adapted from the P-11. The PF-9 is nearly identical to the P-11 in length and height and shares the same exterior controls. The shorter trigger system with integral hammer block and the extraction system are adapted from the P-3AT. Just like the P-11, the PF-9 will accept +P ammunition, however, not with continuous use.


     The rear sight is a new design and is adjustable for windage with the supplied allen wrench as well as for elevation with the use of shims (not included). The included 7 round rectangular magazine is supplied with a finger extension base plate and numbered holes. The under barrel accessory rail shares the dimensions of the MIL-STD-1913 picatinny rail although there is only one locking notch in the forward position.

title: For Sale:  Rare Sino Soviet SKS
postcontent:
I have for sale a Rare Sino Soviet SKS Carbine. These were made in the first half of 1956 in China under Russian watch, Russia had sent a team of advisor's to China to show them how to manufacture the SKS Carbine. The S/N is to the left of the Arsenal 26 (Jianshe) mark and has a weird letter before the 4 digit S/N, that's how to tell this is a Sino Soviet. It has the correct Russian rear sight and uses a blade bayonet.

Someone has ground the bayonet lug off and the cleaning rod lug off as well. Was gonna keep it and put a new front sight block on it so I can take it back to it's Military form but I've decided to part with it. This SKS functions flawlessly, it's numbers matching except the magazine and stock, which is common with these. Bore is nice and bright with sharp rifling!

The SKS being sold is the one on the top in the pics, the lighter of the two with the sling and without the bayonet, the bottom one(my numbers matching Romanian)IS NOT FOR SALE!

$350 is a steal!

I live in Sapulpa, if interested in the SKS please Call or Text REDACTED
